is that as misers and men of ambition‚ who can rebuke avarice and ambition in others, are not miserly or ambitious by natural necessity but by their own choice, so those who give way to grief, though able to console others in grief, grieve not natura sed iudicio.

§ 74. hoc: defined by cum constet aeg. uet. tolli.

experimentum: though this word, in the sense ofdecumentum,‘proof,' is chiefly post-Augustan, it seems the only possible reading here. exprimendum, of most MSS, would seem to involve, as Or. says, the reading maxime, and the meaning hoc maxime cogendi sunt, ut fateantur would not be naturally expressed. Mo. thinks that maximum is not impossible in the sense of hoc quod maximum est with exprimendum explained as above.

hanc uim, ‘this effect,' the power of making people forget.
